02:10:08.740 --> 02:10:12.250
Hello? They are never-been-worn'
$400 shoes.

1683
02:10:12.410 --> 02:10:17.290
Actually 525.
Yeah, okay. All right, thanks. Bye.

1684
02:10:18.130 --> 02:10:20.170
Taxi!

1685
02:10:29.640 --> 02:10:33.140
The light in our prewar apartment...

1686
02:10:33.310 --> 02:10:36.600
...looked completely different postwar.

1687
02:10:57.210 --> 02:11:01.920
I was gonna get these to you.
I didn't want it to be a total loss.

1688
02:11:02.210 --> 02:11:06.090
It wasn't logic, it was love.

1689
02:11:27.200 --> 02:11:30.200
Why did we ever decide to get married?

1690
02:11:32.370 --> 02:11:37.870
I guess we were afraid
it would mean something if we didn't.

1691
02:11:42.090 --> 02:11:48.550
I'm sorry to have done that to you.

1692
02:11:52.560 --> 02:11:54.640
You know the funny part?

1693
02:11:56.690 --> 02:11:58.900
Is there a funny part?

1694
02:11:59.060 --> 02:12:03.360
We were perfectly happy before
we decided to live happily ever after.

1695
02:12:03.820 --> 02:12:05.690
Guess the joke's on us.

1696
02:12:14.750 --> 02:12:18.580
- It's a good closet.
- Thanks.

1697
02:12:21.880 --> 02:12:24.250
It's comfortable.

1698
02:12:24.590 --> 02:12:27.920
Is this what you had in mind
when you installed the carpet?

1699
02:12:28.970 --> 02:12:31.970
I'd like to think I was that smooth.

1700
02:12:39.400 --> 02:12:43.230
We better get up
before the new owners bust in on us.

1701
02:12:52.280 --> 02:12:56.040
And the way we decided to get married...

1702
02:12:56.200 --> 02:12:58.120
...it was all business.

1703
02:12:58.290 --> 02:13:00.460
No romance.

1704
02:13:02.960 --> 02:13:08.050
That's not the way
you propose to someone.

1705
02:13:09.470 --> 02:13:11.470
This is.

1706
02:13:14.970 --> 02:13:17.060
Carrie Bradshaw...

1707
02:13:17.770 --> 02:13:19.140
...love of my life...

1708
02:13:22.020 --> 02:13:24.060
...will you marry me?

1709
02:13:28.940 --> 02:13:31.280
See, this is why there's a diamond.

1710
02:13:31.450 --> 02:13:33.570
You need to do something
to close the deal.

1711
02:13:58.140 --> 02:13:59.350
And forsaking all others...

1712
02:13:59.520 --> 02:14:03.390
And in the end, Carrie Bradshaw
married John James Preston...

1713
02:14:03.560 --> 02:14:05.230
...in a label-less dress.
- I do.

1714
02:14:05.690 --> 02:14:08.360
Then by the power vested in me
by the state of New York...

1715
02:14:08.530 --> 02:14:13.110
...I now pronounce you husband and wife.
You may kiss the bride.

1716
02:14:23.710 --> 02:14:25.710
Ever thine. Ever mine.

1717
02:14:26.500 --> 02:14:29.170
Ever ours.

1718
02:14:31.590 --> 02:14:33.930
So you're okay that it was just us?

1719
02:14:34.090 --> 02:14:38.680
It was perfect. You and me, like I said.

1720
02:14:38.850 --> 02:14:42.100
Still, it would have been nice
if you had the girls here.

1721
02:14:43.770 --> 02:14:46.190
Which is why I called them.

1722
02:14:50.480 --> 02:14:53.190
- Hi, Carrie!
- Mazel tov!

1723
02:14:56.410 --> 02:14:59.490
- Ham and eggs. Ham and eggs for you, sir.
- Yup, that's me.

1724
02:14:59.660 --> 02:15:02.330
It wasn't a fancy, designer reception either.

1725
02:15:02.870 --> 02:15:05.000
Just food and friends.

1726
02:15:07.210 --> 02:15:09.090
Butter, ma'am?

1727
02:15:11.340 --> 02:15:13.050
How's the marriage going?

1728
02:15:33.240 --> 02:15:38.410
"And as I put the wedding gown away'
I couldn't help but wonder:

1729
02:15:38.570 --> 02:15:42.790
'Why is it that we're willing
to write our own vows...

1730
02:15:42.950 --> 02:15:46.460
...but not our own rules?"'

1731
02:15:46.670 --> 02:15:49.170
And that's just a little something
I'm working on.

1732
02:15:51.630 --> 02:15:53.380
Thank you.

1733
02:15:55.050 --> 02:15:56.720
Oh, my God.

1734
02:15:59.140 --> 02:16:01.800
Maybe some labels
are best left in the closet.

1735
02:16:01.970 --> 02:16:03.470
Maybe when we label people:

1736
02:16:03.640 --> 02:16:07.890
"Bride," "groom," "husband,"
"wife," "married," "single"...

1737
02:16:08.060 --> 02:16:11.560
...we forget to look past the label
to the person.

1738
02:16:12.770 --> 02:16:15.820
- This is delicious.
- Why did we ever stop drinking these?

1739
02:16:15.990 --> 02:16:19.610
- Because everyone else started.
- Well, that one's an oldie but goodie.

1740
02:16:19.780 --> 02:16:22.580
And speaking of an oldie but goodie...

1741
02:16:25.500 --> 02:16:27.620
- Happy birthday.
- Happy birthday.

1742
02:16:28.580 --> 02:16:30.630
Wait, wait, wait. A toast.

1743
02:16:30.790 --> 02:16:32.340
To Samantha.

1744
02:16:32.500 --> 02:16:35.250
Fifty and fabulous.

1745
02:16:41.350 --> 02:16:43.180
To us...

1746
02:16:44.930 --> 02:16:46.020
...and the next 50.

1747
02:16:46.180 --> 02:16:48.520
To the next 50.

1748
02:16:50.600 --> 02:16:54.980
And there, in the same city
where they met as girls...

1749
02:16:55.150 --> 02:16:59.490
...four New York women
entered the next phase of their lives...

1750
02:16:59.660 --> 02:17:03.280
...dressed head to toe in love.

1751
02:17:03.910 --> 02:17:06.120
And that's the one label...

1752
02:17:06.290 --> 02:17:09.500
...that never goes out of style.

